For example,
```lean
(prod_assoc% : (Œ± √ó Œ≤) √ó (Œ≥ √ó Œ¥) ‚âÉ Œ± √ó (Œ≤ √ó Œ≥) √ó Œ¥)
```
gives the "obvious" equivalence between `(Œ± √ó Œ≤) √ó (Œ≥ √ó Œ¥)` and `Œ± √ó (Œ≤ √ó Œ≥) √ó Œ¥`.

Special thanks to @kmill for help getting the expected type to work in the elaborator!

Something that occurred to me is that we could have probably used the coherence theorem for monoidal categories and the `coherence` tactic to do all this "for free" (you're using `List` to strictify the products after all :smile:) but I believe you're generating much much better code, if this elaborator gets used in programming.

I don't see any obvious bugs, so let's just merge

bors r+

There's one suggested efficiency improvement, but the arrays involved are so small we'd probably not detect the difference, though it would make the code look cleaner. I figure it can be a follow-up.

```suggestion
/-- IMPLEMENTATION: Syntax used in the implementation of `prod_assoc%`.
This elaborator postpones if there are metavariables in the expected type,
and to propagate the fact that this elaborator produces an `Equiv`,
the `prod_assoc%` macro sets things up with a type ascription.
This enables using `prod_assoc%` with, for example `Equiv.trans` dot notation. -/
```
(I tried explaining it. Feel free to improve.)
LGTM!

````suggestion
`prod_assoc%` elaborates to the "obvious" equivalence between iterated products of types,
regardless of how the products are parenthesized.
The `prod_assoc%` term uses the expected type when elaborating.
For example, `(prod_assoc% : (Œ± √ó Œ≤) √ó (Œ≥ √ó Œ¥) ‚âÉ Œ± √ó (Œ≤ √ó Œ≥) √ó Œ¥)`.

The elaborator can handle holes in the expected type, so long as they eventually get filled by unification.
```lean
example : (Œ± √ó Œ≤) √ó (Œ≥ √ó Œ¥) ‚âÉ Œ± √ó (Œ≤ √ó Œ≥) √ó Œ¥ :=
  (prod_assoc% : _ ‚âÉ Œ± √ó Œ≤ √ó Œ≥ √ó Œ¥).trans prod_assoc%
```
````
Thanks. Done!
Could you move these examples to `test/ProdAssoc.lean`?
Will do!

Done, and added a few more examples, including this one which I think is quite cool:
```lean
example (x : Œ±) (y : Œ≤) (z : Œ≥) (w : Œ¥) :
    prod_assoc% ((x,y),(z,w)) = (x,(y,z),w) :=
  rfl
```
Wow, I hadn't anticipated that that would work!

It's a little overkill (`e.consumeMData` is probably all you need in practice), but if you want to avoid some metadata-related issues you probably should do
```suggestion
  match e.cleanupAnnotations with
```
You might even consider `whnfR` instead of `cleanupAnnotations` if you want this elaborator to unfold reducible definitions, but I'm assuming we don't want that, since it could be rather surprising.
I did indeed purposefully avoid reduction. But I'll added `cleanupAnnotations` as suggested.
I think you should do `(‚Üê whnfD (‚Üê inferType X)).type?` here since the type might not literally be `Type _`, and it might need a bit of reduction.
Done. Thanks!

Small typo, and I'd suggest writing the message out like this:
```suggestion
      throwError "Component{indentD x}\nis not definitionally equal to component{indentD y}."
```
Done. Thanks!

To help readability if the terms are long.
```suggestion
    throwError "The number of components in{indentD a}\nand{indentD b}\nmust match."
```
Done. Thanks!
Is constructing this `.lam` necessary? It looks like `pa.convertTo pb` is all you need to return, unless the point of this is to cache the type of the domain for some reason?

I'm not sure what you mean. This is meant to construct the actual function, as an `Expr`, between the products. `pa.convertTo pb` will return a function `Expr -> Expr`, so constructing some `.lam` term will have to be done later, presumably as part of `mkProdEquiv`. I can imagine it being useful to have some way to construct the `Expr` of the function, which this accomplishes.

Oh, oops, I got lost in the levels of representation here. I mistook the application for a `.app`.

Passing `.bvar 0` like this isn't exactly safe, unless you are very careful that you never use `.lam` ever again inside the term. You don't, so it's ok I think, but the way you're supposed to do this is
```
withLocalDeclD `t a fun fvar =>
  mkLambdaFVars #[fvar] (‚Üê pa.convertTo pb fvar)
```
(untested, I might have gotten function names and argument orders wrong). If you don't switch to using `mkLambdaFVars`, please document the invariants why `.bvar 0` is OK.
Ah I see. Okay I'll make this change soon. I actually had to fight this `bvar` while I was writing this code, so I know for a fact that this is brittle. Thanks!
Ok. I've fixed this now, essentially using your suggestion with `withLocalDeclD`.
Same `whnfD` consideration for these `.type?` functions as in my other comment.
Thanks. Done!

This error should never happen, but let's make it look nice anyway.
```suggestion
          | throwError "Expected type{indentD expectedType}\nis not of the form `Œ± ‚âÉ Œ≤`."
```
Thanks. Done!
I believe you could make this take an `Subarray Expr`, which would save you needing to do these to-and-from-array conversions.
Good idea! I'll implement this in a follow up PR.
